      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can modify the script to back up the test results and session state to an external mount or persistent volume. Here's an example:\n\n```bash\n#!/bin/bash\n\n# Run validation suite\nvalidation_suite_command=\"your_validation_suite_command_here\"\n\n# Backup test results and session state\nBACKUP_DIR=/mnt/persistent_backup\nmkdir -p $BACKUP_DIR\nDATE=$(date -d \"today\" +%Y-%m-%d)\nBACKUP_FILE=$BACKUP_DIR/$(basename $validation_suite_command)_$(date +%s).txt\necho \"Running validation suite and backing up results...\" >&2\n$validation_suite_command >> $BACKUP_FILE\necho \"Test results backed up to $BACKUP_DIR\"\n\n# Check system logs\nLOGFILE=/var/log/system.log\nLOG_DATE=$(date -d \"today\" +%Y-%m-%d)\necho \"Checking system logs for $LOG_DATE...\"\ntail -f $LOGFILE | grep \"cleanup tasks\" | grep \"scheduled container resets\"\n```\n\nIn this example, I've added a `BACKUP_DIR` variable that points to an external mount or persistent volume. The script creates a subdirectory within this mount point, generates a unique backup filename based on the validation",
